04538nam a22005535i 9780520354227DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203542277 a10.1525/97805203542272doi  a(DE-B1597)647759  a(OCoLC)1414455909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aREL0400002bisacsh1 aGoitein/Lassner, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMediterranean Society, An Abridgment in One Volume /cGoitein/Lassner; ed. by S. D. Goitein, Jacob Lassner. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (528 p.) :b1 b/w photograph, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAuthor's Note -- tMap: The Mediterranean in the eleventh century -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: COMMUNAL ORGANIZATION -- t1. Jewish Ecumenical and Territorial Authorities -- t2. The Local Community -- t3. Community Officials -- t4. The Social Services -- t5. Houses of Worship -- t6. Jews and the Muslim State as Reflected in the Geniza -- t7. A Social Being -- t8. Social Structure -- t9. Education and the Professional Class -- t10. Interfaith Relations -- t11. Communal Jurisdiction -- tPart II: The Family and Its Values -- tIntroduction -- t12. The House of the Father -- t13. Marriage -- t14. The "House" or Nuclear Family -- t15. The World of Women -- tAddendum -- tGeneral Index -- tIndex of Scriptural Citations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aS. D. Goitein's magisterial five-volume work on Jewish communities in the medieval Mediterranean world offers an unparalleled view of how people lived, traveled, worshiped, and conducted their economic and social affairs. Living under Muslim rule, the Jews became increasingly urbanized and played a significant part in an expanding world economy. As major actors in the flourishing intellectual life of the period, they forged much of what constitutes traditional Judaism today and served as a conduit of Islamic learning to the Christian West.Goitein's masterpiece is now abridged and reworked by Jacob Lassner in a single volume that captures the essential narratives and contexts of the original. To understand the value of this distillation, we need to picture the remarkable, all-but-impenetrable cache of unique letters and documents found by accident in a geniza, or repository of sacred writings, in Old Cairo. These materials, unlike historical chronicles and literary texts of the time, represent the living experiences of people in a wide variety of settings throughout the entire Mediterranean and stretching as far east as the Indian subcontinent.Goitein explored and interpreted these texts as no other scholar had. Lassner, in turn, makes Goitein's findings available to a wide audience and then moves on to raise a host of new and tantalizing questions about the Jews of the Geniza and the relationship of their community to the hegemonic Muslim society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGeneral. 4aJudaism. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aGoitein, S. D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLassner, Jacob, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024059940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035422740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520354227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520354227/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-a